SIMPLE: inviolable
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inviolable
<hw>In*vi"o*la*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>inviolabilis</ets>: cf. F. <ets>inviolable</ets>. See
<er>Inviolate</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Not violable; not susceptible of hurt, wound, or
harm (used with respect to either physical or moral damage); not
susceptible of being profaned or corrupted; sacred; holy; <as>as,
<ex>inviolable</ex> honor or chastity; an <ex>inviolable</ex>
shrine.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He tried a third, a tough, well-chosen spear,⟦br⟧
The <qex>inviolable</qex> body stood sincere.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Unviolated; uninjured; undefiled;
uncorrupted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For thou, be sure, shalt give account⟦br⟧
To him who sent us, whose charge is to keep⟦br⟧
This place <qex>inviolable</qex>, and these from harm.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Not capable of being broken or violated; <as>as, an
<ex>inviolable</ex> covenant, agreement, promise, or vow</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their almighty Maker first ordained⟦br⟧
And bound them with <qex>inviolable</qex> bands.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And keep our faiths firm and <qex>inviolable</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inviolableness</ent>⟦br⟧
